WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.560
You've covered a lot of ground.

2
00:00:02.120 --> 00:00:07.460
Sellers, the offer, the pipeline, scripts,
objections, tools,

3
00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:13.680
KPIs, compensation, advanced situations,
FAQs.

4
00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:18.520
Now we're going to put all of it together
into what a real day actually looks like.

5
00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:20.780
Because knowing the pieces is one thing.

6
00:00:21.180 --> 00:00:23.300
Running the whole day is something else.

7
00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.960
You clock in on Hubstaff and open Sandra.

8
00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:28.480
That's your command center.

9
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.400
First thing you do is look at your follow-up
list.

10
00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:33.760
How many callbacks are scheduled for today?

11
00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:35.340
What stage are they in?

12
00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:36.860
Who's the hottest lead?

13
00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:39.720
The one closest to being ready for a
handoff.

14
00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:45.660
Sort your priorities. Stage 3, leads come
first because they're closest to moving

15
00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:46.200
forward.

16
00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:50.200
Then stage 2, the ones that still need
qualification.

17
00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:54.920
Then stage 1, people you haven't been able
to connect with yet.

18
00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:02.060
For the first half hour, you open PropStream
and do quick research on your top 10 to 15

19
00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:08.080
leads. Verify ownership, check property
details, look for anything useful.

20
00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:13.760
Liens, tax status, mortgage info, anything
you can reference on the call.

21
00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:18.880
This half hour of prep makes every conversation
you have for the rest of the day better.

22
00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:22.980
You'll sound like you've done your homework
because you actually did.

23
00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:26.020
Then you start dialing.

24
00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:29.040
Your first calling block is the most
important one.

25
00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:31.780
Follow-ups first. Always.

26
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:36.420
Start with your scheduled callbacks, the
people who are expecting to hear from you at a

27
00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:37.400
specific time.

28
00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:41.820
After that, move to the other follow-up
leads in your pipeline.

29
00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.280
Then new leads that haven't been contacted.

30
00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:47.940
You're aiming for 60 to 80 dials in this
first block.

31
00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:52.540
After every call, you log notes in Sandra
immediately.

32
00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:55.760
Between dials, you fire off follow-up texts.

33
00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:58.860
Take a break. Seriously.

34
00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:01.980
Step away from the screen for 15 minutes.

35
00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:04.240
Stretch. Get some water.

36
00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.840
Reset your energy. The next block needs the
same energy as the first one, and it won't

37
00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:11.560
get it if you're running on fumes.

38
00:02:12.780 --> 00:02:16.320
Second calling block. Keep working your
list.

39
00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:20.080
Mix in texts and emails between calls.

40
00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:26.620
If you cleared all your follow-ups in the
first block, focus on new leads and

41
00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:27.280
re-contacts.

42
00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:33.880
By the time you break for lunch, you should
be somewhere around 110 to 150 dials for

43
00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:34.320
the day.

44
00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:40.260
Lunch. Eat real food, not a protein bar at
your desk while scrolling your phone.

45
00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:44.020
After lunch, you've got an admin block.

46
00:02:44.900 --> 00:02:48.260
Send follow-up emails for the conversations
you had that morning.

47
00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:51.540
Update lead stages in the CRM.

48
00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:55.700
If any leads are ready for handoff, complete
those checklists now.

49
00:02:56.180 --> 00:02:57.940
Clean up any notes that need detail.

50
00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:00.900
Then your final calling block.

51
00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:03.060
This is the last push.

52
00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:05.560
Hit the remaining leads on your list.

53
00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:09.200
Try re-dials on the people who didn't pick
up in the morning.

54
00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:12.760
Make sure every lead scheduled for today has
been attempted.

55
00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:17.700
By the end of this block, you should be at
150 to 200 total dials.

56
00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:21.880
Last half hour of the day is pipeline
review.

57
00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:24.420
Step back and look at the big picture.

58
00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:27.120
How many leads are sitting at each stage?

59
00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:32.420
Are there any stuck in stage one that
haven't connected after multiple attempts?

60
00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:34.340
Maybe they need a different approach?

61
00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:38.840
Are there any in stage three that are ripe
for handoff but haven't been moved yet?

62
00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:44.820
Update every stage. Make sure every active
lead has a next action with a specific date.

63
00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.500
No leads floating around without a plan.

64
00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.060
Then schedule your follow-ups for tomorrow.

65
00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:54.840
Make sure your task list in Sandra is ready
for when you sit down in the morning.

66
00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:56.900
Clean up anything that's stale.

67
00:03:57.460 --> 00:03:58.020
Clock out.

68
00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:02.180
You've worked the day when all of this is
true.

69
00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:03.880
You hit your dial target.

70
00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:06.520
You completed every scheduled follow-up.

71
00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:09.500
You logged detailed notes on every
conversation.

72
00:04:09.780 --> 00:04:13.100
You sent follow-up texts and emails to all
active leads.

73
00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:16.360
You updated all lead stages that needed
updating.

74
00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:19.180
Every active lead has a next action.

75
00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:20.820
Your pipeline is clean.

76
00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.000
And you clocked your full hours.

77
00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:26.420
If all of that is true, you worked the day.

78
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:29.840
It doesn't matter if nobody picked up.

79
00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:32.280
It doesn't matter if you didn't close a
deal.

80
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.940
You controlled what you could control.

81
00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:41.700
And over time, over weeks and months, that
consistency is what produces results.

82
00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:44.080
It's not one heroic day.

83
00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:47.140
It's showing up and doing it every single
day.

84
00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:49.680
This job is a marathon.

85
00:04:50.260 --> 00:04:54.780
You're making 150-plus calls a day, five
days a week.

86
00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.200
If you don't manage your energy, you will
burn out.

87
00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:03.180
Smile before you dial because people can
hear your energy through the phone.

88
00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:06.040
Take your breaks. Don't skip them.

89
00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:08.840
Stay hydrated. Eat real food.

90
00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:13.460
If you're having a rough stretch on the
phone and nothing's connecting, take a

91
00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:15.300
five-minute walk outside and reset.

92
00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:17.940
Celebrate small wins throughout the day.

93
00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.480
A good conversation. A lead that moved to
the next stage.

94
00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:24.940
A callback that finally connected.

95
00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:26.400
Those add up.

96
00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:28.620
And remember something.

97
00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:32.020
It takes one call to completely change your
day.

98
00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:36.860
One conversation can turn a zero day into
the best day you've had.

99
00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:39.800
This is a numbers game, but it's run by
humans.

100
00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:43.440
The numbers matter. The consistency matters.

101
00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:49.240
But the thing that actually makes it work is
the genuine care you bring to every

102
00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:54.380
conversation. The sellers who close with us
do it because someone cared enough to keep

103
00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:59.660
calling, to keep listening, to follow
through when everyone else dropped off.

104
00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:01.680
That's what this job is.

105
00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:04.960
Your capstone roleplay is coming.

106
00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:10.540
A full cycle scenario, cold outreach all the
way through to framing the handoff.

107
00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:12.980
Everything you've learned is on the table.

108
00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:15.360
But before you run it, one more piece.

109
00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:18.600
How the team stays in sync day to day.
